Super Eagles’ first-choice goalkeeper, Maduka Okoye has been the cynosure of all eyes especially ladies in the ongoing Africa Cup of Nations (AFCON) 2021. Nicknamed “Madu”, his good looks and impressive physique has set many tongues wagging. Okoye’s profile has been on the rise since the youngster became a Nigerian international. The German-born goalie made his debut for the Super Eagles against Brazil in October 2019 when he was valued at €150,000 and still struggling at Fortuna Dusseldorf. The German-born goalie played for the youth teams of Bayer Leverkusen and Fortuna Düsseldorf prior to his transfer to Sparta Rotterdam in July 2020. - Advertisement - On the back of his excellent performances in 2020-2021, Sparta Rotterdam extended Okoye’s contract and they are hoping to make a tidy profit if he is sold before June 2025. 1. Maduka Emilio Okoye (born 28 August 1999) was born in Düsseldorf to a Nigerian father and a German mother. 2. He left Nigeria at six and did not return for 14 years.   ROUND OF 16 CRACKER: Nigeria faces old foe Tunisia as…     Bayelsa vows to weed out illegal academic institutions     Okowa dissolves Delta State Traditional Rulers’…   3. Born of Enugu-Nigeria father and a German mother, he spent brief times in Enugu, Abuja, and Lagos before he was ferried to Germany where he spent his formative years and become a professional footballer 4. He was groomed at Bayer Leverkusen’s academy before joining Fortuna Dusseldorf in 2017 where he has been manning the post for the reserves. 5. In July 2020, Okoye signed for Eredivise side Sparta Rotterdam. 6. On 30 November 2017, former coach Gernot Rohr talked about his plans to invite Maduka to the National Team before the 2018 World Cup but the plans weren’t successful 7. On 20 February 2019, during an interview conducted by German-based sports journalist, Oma Akatugba, Maduka hinted that he’s open to an invitation by the National Team and ever willing to wear the green and white. 8. On 22 February 2019, he was invited to the Nigerian U23 Team for the 2019 African U-23 Cup of Nations qualifier against Libya U-23 by Imama Amapakabo, the coach of the Nigeria U23 Team, but failed to make a debut, due to club engagement. 9. On 9 May 2019, Maduka was again invited to the Nigerian U23 Team for the 2019 African U-23 Cup of Nations qualifier against Sudan U-23. 10. On 26 July 2019, the coach of the Nigerian National Team, Gernot Rohr, hinted that he is shifting his focus to Maduka as he looks to solve the goalkeeping crisis that has rocked his team since Carl Ikeme quit due to illness. 11. On 14 August 2019, Rohr invited Maduka for a friendly against Ukraine that was played on 10 September 2019 in Dnipro-Arena. 12. On 13 October 2019, he made his international debut as a substitute in a friendly match against Brazil, ending 1–1.